> In a FidoNet debate, it's been charged that PGP is unsafe, and that NSA

Take everything you hear on FidoNet with a grain of salt.

> can crack it.  The persons holding this viewpoint espouse the idea that
> the NSA can crack anything, pretty much, and that anything they could not

Yeah, right, they can crack everything, including the Super-Duper
Martian War Code. :-) Or even the one-time pad. :-))

> crack would not be available to the general public, but would have been
> supressed.

Well, if this is reassuring to you, the US gevernment is *already*
trying to supress PGP. I can't say that it is NSA behind all of it,
because their cativities are secret; so you'll have to make your
conclusions yourself.

> Can anyone disprove this notion definitively?  I'm looking for an

How can you prove a negative? Better ask the person who claims that to
prove his claims with anything more than wild speculations. Besides,
those in the know (the NSA folks) wouldn't be allowed to speak.
Therefore, those who speak are not in the know... :-)

